  "suggestion": "[cognitive-psychology+pattern-recognition+clinical-psychology+psycholinguistics] IMPLEMENT NOW — Psychological Archetype Pattern Library (fast pre-classifier). Add a pattern-matching layer that fires BEFORE active inference. Define ~16 situation archetypes (threat-response, loss-aversion, social-exclusion, autonomy-violation, cognitive-dissonance, attachment-threat, goal-obstruction, unexpected-gain, unfairness, humiliation, betrayal, failure, illness, loneliness, novelty-overwhelm, achievement). Each archetype has a canonical {emotion, behavior, rootCause, process} tuple grounded in the literature. Classification: score each archetype by (stimulus.type match × person.needs overlap × context.socialSetting match). If top archetype score > 0.6, blend archetype output 70% with active inference 30%. This gives the model a 'vocabulary' of specific human situations, dramatically improving precision on benchmarks that map to well-studied phenomena. — Math: archetype_score(A, s) = w1·TypeMatch(A.stimulusType, s.stimulus.type) + w2·NeedOverlap(A.needs, s.person.needs) + w3·ContextMatch(A.context, s.context). Output = argmax_A score(A, s). If score > θ=0.6: response = 0.7·archetype[A].template + 0.3·activeInference(s).; [cognitive-psychology+schema-theory+computational-linguistics+emotion-theory] Script-Deviation Emotion Generator (Schank & Abelson 1977). Every situation has an implicit expected script. Emotion is a function of how far reality deviates from script and in which direction. Deviation magnitude → arousal. Deviation valence (better or worse than expected) → emotion type. Implement: for each domain, define the default expected script as a (need, fulfillment_level) vector. Compute deviation = actual_stimulus_impact - expected. Positive deviation + high magnitude = joy/surprise/excitement. Negative deviation + high magnitude = fear/anger/grief. Low deviation = calm/boredom. This elegantly unifies all emotion prediction into one formula and explains why surprises (even good ones) are arousing. — Math: deviation = stimulus.intensity × (actual_relevance - domain_expected_relevance). arousal = |deviation| × precision. valence = sign(deviation). emotion = circumplex(valence, arousal). rootCause = 'expectation violation: script predicted ' + expected + ', got ' + actual.; [cognitive-psychology+dual-process-theory+behavioral-economics+neuroscience] Dual-Process Cascade with Cognitive Load Gate (Kahneman 2011). Model two parallel processes: System 1 (fast, heuristic, pattern-based) and System 2 (slow, deliberate, rule-based). Add a cognitive load metric: load = stimulus.novelty × stimulus.intensity × (1 / (1 + person.needs.length)). If load < 0.4: System 1 dominates (return archetype match or domain prior directly). If load > 0.7: System 2 dominates (run full active inference pipeline). Middle zone: blend both. Modulate threshold by arousal: high arousal lowers the S2 threshold (anxiety makes people think more carefully or freeze). This single mechanism explains why cognitive biases appear under low-load conditions (S1 unchecked) but not under deliberate reflection (S2 engaged). — Math: load = stimulus.novelty × stimulus.intensity / (1 + person.needs.length). s2_threshold = 0.6 - 0.2 × (person.arousal - 0.5). system = load < s2_threshold ? 'S1' : 'S2'. response = α(load)·S1_response + (1-α(load))·S2_response where α = sigmoid(s2_threshold - load).",
